The paper deals with automata and transducers, which are fundamental concepts in theoretical computer science. The focus is on regular languages and word-to-word transformations, which are topics typically studied in the formal language theory (cs.FL) and automata theory (cs.DS) sub-categories. The paper also discusses monadic second-order logic (MSO), which is a topic in logic (cs.LO) and has connections to automata theory. The use of nested words to model unranked trees suggests a connection to formal language theory and parsing (cs.PL). Finally, the paper proposes a new computational model and discusses its algorithmic properties, which are topics typically studied in theoretical computer science (cs.THEORY).
